text=BOOK XXXIII. %0a%0aTHE NATURAL HISTORY OF METALS. 1 %0a%0aCHAP. 1. (1.) — METALS. %0a%0a"We are now about to speak of metals, of actual wealth, 1 ' %0athe standard of comparative value, objects for which we dili- %0agently search, within the earth, in numerous ways. In one %0aplace, for instance, we undermine it for the purpose of obtaining %0ariches, to supply the exigencies of life, searching for either %0agold or silver, electrum 2 or copper. 3 In another place, to %0asatisfy the requirements of luxury, our researches extend to %0agems and pigments, with which to adorn our fingers 4 and the %0awalls of our houses : while in a third place, we gratify Our %0arash propensities by a search for iron, which, amid wars and %0acarnage, is deemed more acceptable even than gold. We trace %0aout all the veins of the earth, and yet, living upon it, under- %0amined as it is beneath our feet, are astonished that it should oc- %0acasionally cleave asunder or tremble : as though, forsooth, these %0a%0a1 We now enter upon the Sixth division of Pliny's work, containing an %0aaccount of mineral substances of all descriptions. — Dr. Bostock. %0a%0al * " Ipsae opes." The metals were looked upon by the ancients as the %0aonly true riches. It is in this sense that Ovid says, Metam. B. i. : " Effo- %0adiuntur opes, irritamenta malorum." Pliny applies the term " pretia re- %0arum" to metals, as forming the unit of value. %0a%0a2 Electrum is described in c. 23, as gold mixed with a certain quan- %0atity of silver. The word " electrum " is also used to signify amber, as in %0aB. iii. c. 30. — B. %0a%0a3 ".5Ss ;" by " aes" is here probably meant copper, as the author is speaking %0aof what is dug out of the earth ; it is more fully described in the first two %0aChapters of the next Book. According to the analysis of Klaproth, the %0ates of the ancients, when employed in works of art, cutting instruments, %0astatues, vases, &c, was the " bronze " of the moderns, a mixture of copper %0aand tin, in which the proportion of tin varied, from a little more than 2 %0ato 1.14 per cent, according as the object was to procure a flexible or a %0ahard substance. Agricola speaks of " aes" as synonymous with "cuprum," %0aand Pliny will be found several times in the present Book, speaking of %0a"aes Cyprium," meaning probably the finest kind of copper, and that with- %0aout alloy. — B. %0a%0a4 Pliny has already referred to this topic in B. ii. c. 63.— B. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 2.] %0a%0a%0a%0aGOLD. %0a%0a%0a%0a69 %0a%0a%0a%0asigns could be any other than expressions of the indignation %0afelt by our sacred parent ! We penetrate into her entrails, and %0aseek for treasures in the abodes even of the Manes, 4 * as though %0aeach spot we tread upon were not sufficiently bounteous and %0afertile for us ! %0a%0aAnd yet, amid all this, we are far from making remedies the %0aobject of our researches : and how few in thus delving into the %0aearth have in view the promotion of medicinal knowledge ! For %0ait is upon her surface, in fact, that she has presented us with %0athese substances, equally with the cereals, bounteous and ever %0aready, as she is, in supplying us with all things for our benefit ! %0aIt is what is concealed from our view, what is sunk far be- %0aneath her surface, objects, in fact, of no rapid formation, 6 that %0aurge us to our ruin, that send us to tbe very depths of hell. %0aAs the mind ranges in vague speculation, let us only consider, %0aproceeding through all ages, as these operations are, when will %0abe the end of thus exhausting the earth, and to what point %0awill avarice finally penetrate ! How innocent, how happy, how %0atruly delightful even would life be, if we were to desire no- %0athing but what is to be found upon the face of the earth ; in a %0aword, nothing but what is provided ready to our hands ! %0a%0aCHAT. 2. GOLD. %0a%0aGold is dug out of the earth, and, in close proximity to it, %0achrysocolla, 6 a substance which, that it may appear all the %0amore precious, still retains the name 7 which it has borrowed %0afrom gold. 8 It was not enough for us to have discovered one %0abane for the human race, but we must set a value too upon the %0avery humours of gold. 9 While avarice, too, was on the search %0a%0a*" Or shades below. 5 " Ilia quae non nascuntur repente." %0a%0as •' Chrysocolla" is fully described in Chapter 26 of this Book. — B. %0a" Meaning "gold glue," or "gold solder." %0a%0a8 There is considerable variation in the text of this passage, as found in %0athe different editions. In that of Dalechamps, the Variorum, and those of %0aDe Lae't and Sillig, the sentence concludes with the words " nomen ex auro %0acustodiens;" while in those of Valpy, Lemaire, Poinsinet, Ajasson, and %0aothers, we find substituted for them the words, "Non natura," " Nomen %0anatnra," " Nomine natura," or "Nomen naturam." — B. The first reading %0ais warranted by the Bamberg MS. %0a%0a» " Auri sanies." More properly speaking, " the corrupt matter dis- %0acharged by gold." See Chapter 26. %0a%0a%0a%0a70 %0a%0a%0a%0aplint's natural histoet. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XXXIII. %0a%0a%0a%0afor silver, it congratulated itself upon the discovery of miuiuni, lc %0aand devised a use to be made of this red earth. %0a%0aAlas for the prodigal inventions of man ! in how many %0aways have we augmented the value of things !" In addition %0ato the standard value of these metals, the art of painting lends %0aits aid, and we have rendered gold and silver still more costly %0aby the art of chasing them. Man has learned how to challenge %0aboth Nature and art to become the incitements to vice ! His %0avery cups he has delighted to engrave with libidinous subjects, %0aand" he takes pleasure in drinking from vessels of obscene form ! 1J %0aBut in lapse of time, the metals passed out of fashion, and %0amen began to make no account of them ; gold and silver, in %0afact, became too common. From this same earth we have ex- %0atracted vessels of murrhine 13 and vases of crystal, 13 * objects %0athe very fragility of which is considered to enhance their value. %0aIn fact, it has come to be looked upon as a proof of opulence, %0aand as quite the glory of luxury, to possess that which may be %0airremediably destroyed in an instant. Nor was even this %0aenough ; — we now drink from out of a mass of gems, 11 and we %0aset our goblets with smaragdi ; 15 we take delight in possessing %0athe wealth of India, as the promoter of intoxication, and gold %0ais now nothing more than a mere accessory. 16 %0a%0a10 " Minium " is treated of in Chapter 36 of this Book. — B. %0a%0a11 "Pretia rerum." The value of the raw material. %0a%0a12 Pliny here refers both to the art of producing figures in relief on drink- %0aing vessels made of the precious metals, and also of giving them particular %0aforms. A well-known line of Juvenal, Sat. ii. 1. 95, affords a striking %0aillustration of the depraved taste which existed in his time. — B. Lampri- %0adius also speaks of vessels of silver " denied with representations of a most %0alibidinous character ;" and Capitolinus speaks of " phallovitroboli," glass %0adrinking vessels shaped like a phallus. %0a%0an "Murrhina" or "myrrhina," are described in B. xxxvii. c. 8; they %0awere, perhaps, onyxes or opals, though possibly the term was not strictly %0aconfined to these substances, but signified any transparent minerals, that %0aexhibited a variety of colours. Salmasius, however, ridicules the idea of %0atheir being onyxes, and is of opinion that these vessels were made of porce- %0alain ; Exer. Plin..p. 144.— B. 13 « See B. xxxvii. c. 9. %0a%0au He alludes to the cups known as " chrysendeta," adorned with cir- %0aclets of gold, exquisite chasings, and groups of precious stones. See Ju- %0avenal, Sat. v. L 42. %0a%0a15 The " Smaragdus" is described in B. xxxvii. c. 13. %0a%0a16 " Et aurum jam accessio est." %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 4.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE OHIGIN OF GOLD KINGS. %0a%0a%0a%0a71 %0a%0a%0a%0aCHAP. 3. WHAT "WAS THR F1KST RECOMMENDATION OF GOLD. %0a%0a"Would that gold could have been banished for ever from %0athe earth, accursed by universal report, 17 as some of the most %0acelebrated writers have expressed themselves, reviled by the %0areproaches of the best of men, and looked upon as discovered %0aonly for the ruin of mankind. How much more happy the %0aage when things themselves were bartered for one another ; as %0awas the case in the times of the Trojan war, if we are to be- %0alieve what Homer says. For, in this way, in my opinion, was %0acommerce then carried on for the supply of the necessaries of %0alife. Some, he tells us, would make their purchases by bartering %0aox-hides, and others by bartering iron or the spoil which they %0ahad taken from the enemy : 18 and yet he himself, already an %0aadmirer of gold, was so far aware of the relative value of tilings, %0athat Glaucus, he informs us, exchanged his arms of gold, valued %0aat one hundred oxen, for those of Diomedes, which were worth %0abut nine. 19 Proceeding upon the same system of barter, many %0aof the fines imposed by ancient laws, at Rome even, were %0alevied in cattle, 20 [and not in money]. %0a%0aCHAP. 4. THE OBIGIN OF GOLD KINGS. %0a%0aThe worst crime against mankind was committed by him %0awho was the first to put a ring upon his fingers: and yet we %0aare not informed, by tradition, who it was that first did so. For %0aas to all the stories told about Prometheus, I look upon them as %0autterly fabulous, although I am aware that the ancients used %0ato represent him with a ring of iron : it was their intention, %0ahowever, to signify a chain thereby, and not an ornament. %0aAs to the ring of Midas, 21 which, upon the collet being turned %0a%0a17 " Sacrum famae." This is the reading given by the Bamberg MS. %0ain substitution for " aurum, sacra fames" and other readings of a similar %0anature, in which Pliny was thought by the commentators to allude to the %0afamous lines of Virgil — %0a%0a" Quid non mortalia pectora cogis, %0aAuri sacra fames !" %0aHad he alluded to the passage of Virgil, it is not probable that he would %0ahave used the expression in the plural, " celeberrinii auctores." %0a%0a18 II. B. vii. 11. 472-5. — B. 19 II. B. vi. 1. 236. %0a%0a20 We may infer that this was the reason why the figure of an ox or %0aother animal was impressed on the earliest Boman coins. — B. %0a%0a21 As Ilardouin remarks, ''This story is told by others, of Gyges, and %0anot of Midas." He refers to Cicero, De Off. B. iii. c. 9, in confirmation of %0ahis assertion. — B. Both Gygcs and Midas were noted for their wealth. %0a%0a%0a%0a72 %0a%0a%0a%0apliny's natural history. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XXXIII. %0a%0a%0a%0ainwards, conferred invisibility upon the wearer, who is there %0athat must, not admit, perforce, that this story is even still %0amore fabulous ? It was the hand, aud a sinister 22 hand, too, in %0aevery sense, that first brought gold into such high repute : not %0aa Roman hand, however, for upon that it was the practice to %0awear a ring of iron only, and solely as an indication of war- %0alike prowess. %0a%0aAs to the usage followed by the Koman kings, it is not easy %0ato pronounce an opinion : the statue of Romulus in the Capitol %0awears no ring, nor does any other statue — not that of L. Brutus %0aeven — with the sole exception of those of Nuina and Servius %0aTullius. I am surprised at this absence of the ring, in the %0acase of the Tarquinii more particularly, seeing that they were %0aoriginally from Greece, 22 * a country from which the use of %0agold rings was first introduced ; though even at the present %0aday the people of Lacedaemon are in the habit of wearing rings %0amade of iron. Tarquinius Priscus, however, it is well known, %0awas the first who presented his son with the golden bulla, 23 on %0athe occasion of his slaying an enemy before he had laid aside the %0apraetexta ; 24 from which period the custom of wearing the bulla %0ahas been continued, a distinction confined to the children of %0athose who have served in the cavalry, those of other persons %0asimply wearing a leather thong. 25 Such being the case, I am %0athe more surprised that the statue of this Tarquinius should %0abe without a ring. %0a%0aAnd yet, with reference to the very name of the ring, I find %0athat there has been considerable uncertainty. That given to %0a%0a22 " Sinistra." The play here upon the word "sinister" cannot he so %0awell transferred into the English language ; but it hears reference to the %0adouble meaning of the word, " on the left hand," and " unlucky," " i II— %0aomened," or, as we say " sinister." "We may remark, that rings were %0avery generally employed by the Romans, not merely as ornaments, but as %0aindications of office and rank. — B. %0a%0a22 * From Corinth, it was said : Damaratus of Corinth being the father of %0athe first Tarquin. See B. xxxv. c. 5. %0a%0a23 On the subject of " Bullae," golden balls, worn by the children of the %0anobles, see Dr. Smith's Diet. Antiq. p. 168. — B. %0a%0a24 As to the " Toga praetexta," see B. viii. c. 74. %0a%0a25 " Lorum." This word literally signifies a leather strap or thong, and %0aPliny is supposed by Hardouin to mean simply, that, in this latter case %0athe strap was worn without the bulla, which was in other cases attached to %0ait. Juvenal, Sat. v. 1. 164, speaks of the " lorum " of the children of the %0apoor. — B. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 4.1 %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE OEIGIN OF GOLD RINGS. %0a%0a%0a%0a73 %0a%0a%0a%0ait originally by the Greeks is derived from the finger ; 26 while %0aoar ancestors styled it " ungulus ;" 27 and in later times both %0aGreeks and Latins have given it the name of " symbolum." 28 %0aFor a great length of time, it is quite clear, not even the %0altoman senators wore rings of gold : for rings were given, and %0aat the public expense, to those only who were about to proceed %0aon an embassy to foreign nations, the reason being, I suppose, %0abecause men of highest rank among foreign nations were per- %0aceived to be thus distinguished. Nor was it the practice for %0aany person to wear these rings, except those who for this reason %0ahad received them at the public expense ; and in most in- %0astances, it was without this distinction that the Roman generals %0acelebrated their public triumphs. 29 For whereas an Etruscan %0acrown 30 of gold was supported from behind over the head of %0athe victor, he himself, equally with the slave probably, who %0awas so supporting the crown, had nothing but a ring of %0airon upon his finger. 31 It was in this manner that C. Marius %0acelebrated his triumph over Jugurtha ; and he never as- %0asumed 32 the golden ring, it is said, until the period of his %0athird consulship. 33 Those, too, who had received golden rings %0aon the occasion of an embassy, only wore them when in public, %0aresuming the ring of iron when in their houses. It is in pur- %0asuance of this custom that even at the present day, an iron %0aring 34 is sent by way of present to a woman when betrothed, %0aand that, too, without any stone in it. %0a%0aFor my own part, I do not find that any rings were used in %0athe days of the Trojan "War; at all events, Homer nowhere %0a%0a26 AaKTvXtov, from SuktvXoq, a "finger." %0a%0a27 Festus says that this was the Oscan name for a ring. It would %0aappear to be allied to the word " unguis," which means a nail of the %0afinger or toe, and would perhaps signify a " nail ornament." %0a%0a28 As meaning a seal or signet, lor which purpose, as we shall find ex* %0aplained in the sequel, the ring was used. %0a%0ai9 This seems to be the meaning of " Vulgoque sic triumph abant." %0a%0a30 As to these crowns, see 15. xxi. c. 4. %0a%0a31 As to some other particulars connected with this usage, see the end %0aof B. xxviii. c. 7. %0a%0a32 And yet, as Hardouin remarks, before his time, when Scipio was %0abesieging Carthage, the bodies of the Eoman tribunes, when selected for %0aburial by Ilasdrubal, were distinguished by their rings of gold. The %0aobject of Marius, no doubt, was to ingratiate himself with the upper classes. %0a%0a33 a.u.o. 651. %0a%0a3 * Known as the "anulus pronubus," or "engaged ring," according to %0aDalechamps, %0a%0a%0a%0a74 %0a%0a%0a%0apliny's natural iiistoky. [Book XXX III. %0a%0a%0a%0amakes mention of tliem ; for although he speaks of the practice %0aof sending tablets 35 by way of letter, 36 of clothes and gold and %0asilver plate being kept laid up in chests, 37 still he gives us to %0aunderstand that they were kept secure by the aid of a knot %0atied fast, and not under a seal impressed by a ring. He does %0anot inform us too, that when the chiefs drew lots to ascertain %0awhich one of them should reply to the challenge 38 of the %0aenemj'-, they made any use of rings 39 for the purpose ; and when %0ahe enumerates the articles that were manufactured at the %0aforge 40 of the gods, he speaks of this as being the origin 41 of %0afibulae 42 and other articles of female ornament, such as ear- %0arings for example, but does not make any mention of rings. %0a%0a43 Whoever it was that first introduced the use of rings, he %0adid so not without hesitation ; for he placed this ornament on %0athe left hand, the hand which is generally concealed, 44 whereas, %0aif he had been sure of its being an honourable distinction, it %0awould have been made more conspicuous upon the right. And if %0aany one should raise the objection that this would have acted %0aas an impediment to the right hand, I can only say that the %0ausage in more recent times fortifies my opinion, and that the %0ainconvenience of wearing rings on the left hand would have %0abeen still greater, seeing that it is with the left hand that the %0a%0a3i " Codicillos." II. B. vi. 1. 168. 36 See B. xiii. c. 21. %0a%0a37 Od. B. viii. 11. 424, 443, 447. %0a%0a38 See the Iliad. B. iii. and B. vii. 1. 175, et seq. %0a%0a39 His meaning is, that although icXr/poi were used, lots or halls made of %0aearth, we do not read that the impressions on them were made by the aid %0aof signet-rings. %0a%0a40 %3c%3c Fabricae deum." He alludes to the forge of Vulcan, described in %0athe Eighteenth Book of the Iliad, 1. 400, et seq. %0a%0a41 This seems to be the meaning of " In primordio factitassc." %0a%0a42 The " fibula?" were the brooches of the ancients, consisting of a pin, %0aand of a curved portion furnished with a hook. See Dr. Smith's I»ict. %0aAntiq. p. 417. %0a%0a43 As the meaning of this passage has been the subject of much discus- %0asion with commentators, we give it in full, as found in the Edition of %0aSillig. " Et quisquis primus instituit, cunctanter id fecit, hevis manibus %0alatentibusque induit, cum, si honos securus fuisset, dextra merit ostentan- %0adus. Quodsi impedimentum potuit in eo aliquod intelligi, etiam serior is %0ausus argumentum est, et majus in laeva fuisset, qua scutum capitur." %0aSillig is of opinion that Pliny is here alluding to the reason given by Ateius %0aCapito (quoted in Macrobius, Saturn. B. vii. c. 13), for wearing the ring %0aon the left hand. It was so worn, he says, from an apprehension that %0athe precious stone with which it was set, might receive injury from the %0acontinual use made of the right hand. %0a%0a44 Under the folds of the toga. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 5.] %0a%0a%0a%0aGOLD POSSESSED BY THE ANCIENTS. %0a%0a%0a%0a75 %0a%0a%0a%0ashield is held. "We find mention made too, in Homer, 45 of men %0awearing gold plaited with the hair ; and hence it is that I am %0aat a loss to say whether the practice first originated with %0afemales. %0a%0aCHAP. 5. THE QUANTITY OF GOLD POSSESSED BY THE ANCIENTS. %0a%0aAt Rome, for a long period of time, the quantity of gold %0awas but very small. At all events, after the capture of the %0aCity by the Gauls, when peace was about to be purchased, not %0amore than one thousand pounds' weight of gold could be col- %0alected. I am by no means unaware of the fact that in the %0athird 46 consulship of Pompeius there was lost from the throne %0aof Jupiter Capitolinus two thousand pounds' weight of gold, %0aoriginally placed there by Camillus ; a circumstance which has %0aled most persons to suppose, that two thousand pounds' weight %0awas the quantity then collected. But in reality, this excess %0aof one thousand pounds was contributed from the spoil taken %0afrom the Gauls, amplified as it was by the gold of which they %0ahad stripped the temples, in that part of the City which they %0ahad captured. %0a%0aThe story of Torquatus, 47 too, is a proof that the Gauls were %0ain the habit of wearing ornaments of gold when engaged in %0acombat ; 48 from which it would appear that the sum taken %0afrom the Gauls themselves, and the amount of which they had %0apillaged the temples, were only equal to the amount of gold %0acollected for the ransom, and no more ; and this is what was %0areally meant by the response given by the augurs, that Jupiter %0aCapitolinus had rendered again the ransom twofold. 49 As we %0a%0a45 II. B. xvii. 1. 52. %0a%0a46 The reading in most MSS. is the "fourth consulship." This, how- %0aever, is an error which has been rectified by the Bamberg and some other %0aMSS. Pompey was but thrice consul. M. Crassus was the person generally %0aaccused of the act of robbery here alluded to. %0a%0a41 Who took the golden tore (torques) from the Gaul whom he slew ; %0awhence his name. 48 " Cum auro pugnare solitos." %0a%0a49 " Quod equidem in augurio intellectum est, cum Capitolinus duplum %0areddidisset." The meaning of this passage is obscure, and cannot with %0acertainty be ascertained. Holland renders it, " To the light and know- %0aledge whereof we come by means of revelation from Augurie, which gave %0aus to understand, that Jupiter Capitolinus had rendered again the foresaid %0aBiimme in duple proportion." Littre gives a similar translation. Ajasson %0atranslates it, " This, at least, is what we may presume, from the fact of %0athere being discovered double the amount expected ;" following the ex- %0aplanation given by Hardouin. %0a%0a%0a%0a76 %0a%0a%0a%0aplint's natural history. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XXXIII. %0a%0a%0a%0awere just now speaking on the subject of rings, it may be as %0awell to add, by way of passing remark, that upon the officer w %0ain charge of the Temple of Jupiter Capitolinus being arrested, %0ahe broke the stone of his ring between his teeth, 81 and expired %0aupon the spot, thus putting an end to all possibility of dis- %0acovering the perpetrator of the theft. %0a%0aIt appears, therefore, that in the year of the City 364, when %0aRome was captured by the Gauls, there was but two thousand %0apounds' weight of gold, at the very most ; and this, too, at a %0aperiod when, according to the returns of the census, there were %0aalready one hundred and fifty-two thousand five hundred and %0aseventy-three free citizens in it. In this same city, too, three %0ahundred and seven years later, the gold which C. Marius the %0ayounger 53 conveyed to Praeneste from the Temple of the Capitol %0awhen in flames, and all the other shrines, amounted to thirteen %0athousand pounds' weight, such being the sum that figured in the %0ainscriptions at the triumph of Sylla ; on which occasion it was %0adisplayed in the procession, as well as six thousand pounds' %0aweight of silver. The same Sylla had, the day before, dis- %0aplayed in his triumph fifteen thousand pounds' weight of gold, %0aand one hundred and fifteen thousand pounds' weight of silver, %0athe fruit of all his other victories. %0a%0aCHAP. 6. THE BIGHT OF WEARING GOLD RINGS. %0a%0aIt does not appear that rings were in common use before the %0atime of Cneius Flavius, the son of Annius. This Flavius was %0athe first to publish a table 63 of the days for pleading, 64 which %0atill then the populace had to ascertain each day from a few %0a%0a50 The " aedituus," or " temple keeper." See B. xxxvi. 4. %0a%0a51 Beneath which there was