n denarii per pound ; the middling, worth five denarii ; %0aand the bruised, also known as the " herbaceous " chryso- %0acolla, worth three denarii per pound. Before laying on the %0asanded 88 chrysocolla, they underlay coats of atramentum 87 %0aand parsetonium, 88 substances which make it hold, and im- %0apart a softness to the colours. The parsetonium, as it is %0anaturally very unctuous, and, from its smoothness, extremely %0atenacious, is laid on first, and is then covered with a coat of %0aatramentum, lest the paraDtonium, from its extreme whiteness, %0ashould impart a paleness to the chrysocolla. The kind known %0aas "lutea," derives its name, it is thought, from the plant %0acalled " lutum ;" which itself is often pounded with cseru- %0aleum 89 instead of real chrysocolla, and used for painting, %0a%0apresent Chapter, and Chapter 57 of this Book. Littre renders the words %0a"in lomentum," kept "in the form of powder," without reference to the %0apeculiar pigment known as " lomentum." 82 " Sudore resolutis." %0a%0a83 A strong proof that chrysocolla was a preparation from copper, and %0anot cobalt. Copper owes its name to the Isle of Cyprus, in which it was %0afound in great abundance. See Beckmann's Hist. Inv. Vol. II. p. 480. %0aBohn's Edition. %0a%0a84 The colour now known by painters as Emerald green. %0a%0a86 As a " trigarius." See B. xxviii. c. 72, and B. xxix. c. 5. From %0aSuetonius, c. 18, we learn that the Emperor Caligula, also, had the Circus %0asanded with minium and chrysocolla. Ajasson is of opinion that the %0achrysocolla thus employed was a kind of yellow mica or talc. %0a%0a86 " Arcnosam." He alludes, probably, to the kind previously mentioned %0aas " aspera " or "rough chrysocolla." %0a%0a87 For its identification, see B. xxxiv. cc. 2G, 32. %0aw See B. xxxv. cc. 12, 18. %0a%0a69 Making a spurious kind of " lomentum," possibly, a pigment men- %0ationed in c. 57 of this Book. This passage seems to throw some light, %0aupon the words " in loment