ld and one- %0aseventh part of silver, in addition to the materials above-men- %0ationed, the whole beaten up together. %0a%0a90 As to durability, probablv. %0a%0a91 It was tbe mineral, probably, in an unprepared state. %0a%0a92 Gold-glue or gold- solder. %0a%0a9 3 See B. xxxi. c. 46, as to tbe " nitrum " of Pliny. Galen in de- %0acerning tbe manufacture of " santerna," omits tbe nitre as an ingredient. %0a%0a" Argentosum." Tbe "electrum," probably, mentioned inc 23. %0a%0a%0a%0aCbap. 31.] %0a%0a%0a%0aSILVER, %0a%0a%0a%0a111 %0a%0a%0a%0aCHAP. 30. THE MARVELLOUS OPERATIONS OF NATURE IN SOLDERING %0a%0aMETALLIC SUBSTANCES, AND BRINGING THEM TO A STATE OP %0aPERFECTION. %0a%0aWhile speaking on this subject, it will be as well to annex %0athe remaining particulars, that our admiration may here be %0adrawn to all the marvels presented by Nature in connection %0atherewith. The proper solder for gold is that above described ; %0afor iron, potter's clay ; for copper, when in masses, cadmia, 9 * %0aand in sheets, alum ; for lead and marble, resin. Lead is also %0aunited by the aid of white lead ; K white lead with white lead, %0aby the agency of oil ; stannum, with copper file-dust ; and %0asilver, with stannum. 97 %0a%0aFor smelting copper and iron, pine-wood is the best, Egypt- %0aian papyrus being also very good for the purpose. Gold is %0amelted most easily with a fire made of chaff'. 98 Limestone %0aand Thracian stone" are ignited by the agency of water, this %0alast being extinguished by the application of oil. Fire, how- %0aever, is extinguished most readily by the application of vinegar, %0aviscus, 1 and unboiled eggs. Earth will under no circumstance %0aignite. When charcoal has been once quenched, and then again %0aignited, it gives out a greater heat than before. %0a%0aCHAP. 31. (6.) SILVER. %0a%0aAfter stating these facts, we come to speak of silver ore, %0athe next 2 folly of mankind. Silver is never found but in %0ashafts sunk deep in the ground, there being no