es are still worked, their names being de- %0arived from the persons who were the first to discover them. %0aOne of these mines, which at the present day is still called Bsebelo, %0afurnished Hannibal with three hundred pounds' weight of silver %0aper day. The mountain is already excavated for a distance of %0afifteen hundred 10 paces; and throughout the whole of this %0adistance there are water-bearers 11 standing night and day, %0abaling out the water in turns, regulated by the light of torches, %0aand so forming quite, a river. %0a%0aThe vein of silver that is found nearest the surface is known %0a%0a4 "Plumbum nigrum"— "Black lead," literally : so called by the ancients, %0ain contradistinction to "plumbum alburn," "white lead," our " tin," %0aprobably. %0a%0a5 Lead ore ; identified with " molybdaena " in B. xxxiv. c. 53. Native %0asulphurate of lead is now known as " galena." See Beckmann's Hist. Inv. %0aVol. II. p. 211, where this passage is commented upon. %0a%0a6 This Beckmann considers to be the same as the" galena" above men- %0ationed; half-vitrified lead, the " glatte" of the Germans. %0a%0a7 The specific gravity of lead is 11.352, and of silver only 10.474. %0a« From the words fitr' dXXa, " one after another." %0a%0a9 It is supposed that these shafts were in the neighbourhood of Castulo, %0anow Cazlona, near Linares in Spain. It was at Castulo that Hannibal %0amarried his rich wife Himilce ; and in the hills north of Linares there are %0aancient silver mines still known as Los Fozos de Anibal. %0a%0a10 A mile and a half. %0a%0a%0a%0aThe proper reading here, as suggested by Sillig, is not improbably %0a" aquatini, "water-carriers." That, however, found in the MSS is "Aqui- %0atani ;" but those were a people, not of Spain, but of Gaul. Hardouin sug- %0agests that " Accitam may be the correct reading, a people of that name %0ain Spain being mentioned in B. lii. c. 5. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 32.] %0a%0a%0a%0aQUICKSILVER. %0a%0a%0a%0a113 %0a%0a%0a%0aby the name of "crudaria." 12 In ancient times, the excavations %0aused to be abandoned the moment alum 13 was met with, and no %0afurther 14 search was made. Of late, however, the discovery of %0aa vein of copper beneath alum, has withdrawn any such limits %0ato man's hopes. The exhalations from silver-mines are dan- %0agerous to all animals, but to dogs more particularly. The %0asofter they are, the more beautiful gold and silver are con- %0asidered. It is a matter of surprise with most persons, that lines %0atraced 15 with silver should be black. %0a%0aCHAP. 32. QUICKSILVER. %0a%0aThere is a mineral also found in these veins of silver, which %0ayields a humour that is always 16 liquid, and is known as %0a"quicksilver." 17 It acts as a poison 18 upon everything, and %0apierces vessels even, making its way through them by the %0aagency of its malignant properties. 19 AH substances float upon %0athe surface of quicksilver, with the exception of gold, 20 this %0abeing the only substance that it attracts to itself. 21 Hence %0ait is, that it is such an excellent refiner of gold ; for, on being %0abriskly shaken in an earthen vessel with gold, it rejects all %0athe impurities that are mixed with it. When once it has thus %0aexpelled these superfluities, there is nothing to do but to sepa- %0arate it from the gold ; to effect which, it is poured out upon %0askins that have been well tawed, and so, exuding through them %0alike a sort of perspiration, it leaves the gold in a state of %0apurity behind. 22 %0a%0a12 Meaning " raw" silver, apparently. %0a%0a13 " Alumen." See B. xx%25\. c. 52. %0a%0a14 Kircher speaks of this being still the case in his time. %0a%0a15 See Chapter 19 of this Book. %0a%0a10 " Vomica liquoris aeterni." Mercury or quicksilver becomes solidified %0aand assumes a crystalline texture at 40° below zero. It is found chiefly %0ain the state of sulphuret, which is decomposed by distillation with iron or %0alime. It is also found in a native state. %0a%0a11 " Argentum v