ittle rough. This process is similar to %0athat used at present for gilding with amalgam, by means of heat, especially %0aas amalgamation was known to the ancients. But, to speak the truth, %0aPliny says nothing of heating the metal after the gold is applied, or of %0aevaporating the quicksilver, but of drying the cleaned metal before the %0agold is laid on. Had he not mentioned quicksilver, his gilding might %0ahave been considered as that with gold leaf by means of heat, dorure en %0afeuille a feu, in which the gold is laid upon the metal after it has been %0acleaned and heated, and strongly rubbed with blood-stone, or polished steel. %0aFelibien (Principes de I' Architecture. Paris, 1676, p. 280) was undoubt- %0aedly right when he regretted that the process of the ancients, the excellence %0aof which is proved by remains of antiquity, has been lost." — Hist. Inv. %0aVol. II. pp. 294, 295. Bohn's Edition. %0a%0au Beckmann finds considerable difficulties in this description—" I ac- %0aknowledge that this passage I do not fully comprehend. It seems to say %0athat the quicksilver, when the gold was laid on too thin, appeared through %0ait, but that this might be prevented by mixing with the quicksilver the %0awhite of an egg. The quicksilver then remained under the gold: a thing %0awhich is impossible. When the smallest drop of quicksilver falls upon %0agilding, it corrodes the noble metal, and produces an empty spot. It is, %0atherefore, incomprehensible to me how this could be prevented by using %0athe white of an egg. Did Pliny himself completely understand gilding? %0aPerhaps he only meant to say that many artists gave out the cold-gildiug. %0awhere the gold-leaf was laid on with the white of an e^o- as oildino- bv %0ameans of heat."— Hist. Inv. Vol. II. p. 295. ° 8 ' ° %0a%0a» Chapter 42 of this Book. See also Chapter 20, in Note 20, to which %0ait has been mentioned as artificial quicksilver. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 34.] SEVEN BEMEDIES DEBITED FBOM STIMMT. 115 %0a%0a%0a%0aCHAP. 33. — STXMMI, STIBI, ALABASTBUM, 1ABBASIS, OB PLATY- %0aOPHTHALMON. %0a%0aIn the same mines in which silver is found, there is also %0afound a substance which, properly speaking, may be called a %0astone made of concrete froth. 21 It is white and shining, with- %0aout being transparent, and has the several names of stimmi, %0astibi, alabastrum, 22 and larbasis. There are two kinds of it, %0athe male and the female. 23 The latter kind is the more ap- %0aproved of, the male 24 stimmi being more uneven, rougher to %0athe touch, less ponderous, not so radiant, and more gritty. %0aThe female kind, on the other hand, is bright and friable, and %0aseparates in laminae, and not in globules. 28 %0a%0aCHAP. 34. SEVEN BEMEDIES DEBIVED FBOM STIMMI. %0a%0aStimmi is possessed 'of certain astringent and refrigeratire %0aproperties, its principal use, in medicine, being for the eyes. %0aHence it is that most persons call it "platyophthalmon," 26 it be- %0aing extensively employed in the calliblepharic 27 preparations of %0afemales, for the purpose of dilating the eyes. It acts also as a %0acheck upon fluxes of the eyes and ulcerations of those organs ; %0abeing used, as a powder, with pounded frankincense and gum. %0aIt has the property, too, of arresting discharges of blood from %0a%0a51 He is speaking of Antimony. 22 From its whiteness. %0a%0a23 Under the name of " female stimmi," Ajasson thinks that pure, or %0anative, antimony is meant, more particularly the lamelliform variety, re- %0amarkable for its smoothness. He thinks it possible, also, that it may have %0aderived its Greek name " larbason," or " larbasis," from its brittleness. %0a%0a94 Ajasson thinks that under this name, crude antimony or sulphuret of %0aantimony may have been included ; as also sulphuret of lead, sulphuret of %0aantimony and copper, and sulphuret of antimony and silver ; the last ot %0awhich is often found covered with an opaque pellicle. %0a%0a25 " Globis." The fracture of sulphuret of antimony is, in reality, small %0asuhconchoidal. %0a%0a26 " Eye dilating." Belladonna, a preparation from the Atropa bella- %0adonna, is now used in medicine for this purpose. A similar effect is attri- %0abuted in B. xxv. c. 92, to the plant Anagallis. In reality, the application %0aof prepared antimony would contract the eyelids, and so appear to enlarge %0athe eyes. This property is peculiar, Ajasson remarks, to sulphuret of an- %0atimony, and sulphuret of antimony and silver. , %0a%0a27 Preparations " for beautifying the eyebrows." See B. xxi. c. J 3, B. %0axxiii. c. 51, and B. xxxv. c. 56. Omphale, the Lydian queen, who capti- %0avated Hercules, is represented by the tragic poet Ion, as using "stimmi'' %0afor the purposes of the toilet. It was probably with a preparation of anti- %0amony that Jezebel "painted her face, and tired her head." 2 Kings, ix. 30. %0aThe "Kohl" used by the females in Egypt and Persia is prepared from an- %0atimony. I 2 %0a%0a%0a%0a116 %0a%0a%0a%0aplint's natural HISTORY. [Book XXXIII. %0a%0a%0a%0athe brain; and, sprinkled in the form of a powder, it is extremely %0aefficacious for the cure of recent wounds and bites of dogs which %0ahave been some time inflicted. For the cure of burns it is re- %0amarkably good, mixed with grease, litharge, 28 ceruse, and wax. %0a%0aThe method of preparing it, is to burn it, enclosed in a %0acoat of cow-dung, in a furnace ; which done, it is quenched %0awith woman's milk, and pounded with rain-water in a mortar. 29 %0aWhile this is doing, the thick and turbid part is poured off %0afrom time to time into a copper vessel, and purified with nitre. 30 %0aThe lees of it, which are rejected, are recognized by their %0abeing full of lead and falling to the bottom. The vessel into %0awhich the turbid part has been poured off, is then covered %0awith a linen cloth and left untouched for a night ; the portion %0athat lies upon the surface being poured off the following day, %0aor else removed with a sponge. The part that has fallen to %0athe bottom of the vessel is regarded as the choicest 31 part, and %0ais left, covered with a linen cloth, to dry in the sun, but not %0ato become parched. This done, it is again pounded in a %0amortar, and then divided into tablets. But the main thing of %0aall is, to observe such a degree of nicety in heating it, as not %0ato let it become lead. 32 Some persons, when • preparing it on %0athe fire, use grease 33 instead of dung. Others, again, bruise it %0ain water and then pass it through a triple strainer of linen %0acloth ; after which, they reject the lees, and pour off the %0aremainder of the liquid, collecting all that is deposited at the %0abottom, and using it as an ingredient in plasters and eye- salves. %0a%0aCHAP. 35. — THE SCORIA OF SILVEB. SIX REMEDIES DERIVED FROH IT. %0a%0aThe scoria of silver is called by the Greeks " helcysma." 3 * %0a%0a28 " Spuma argenti." See the next Chapter. %0a%0a29 According to Dioscorides, it was prepared as a cosmetic by enclosing %0ait in a lump of dough, and then burning it in the coals till reduced to a %0acinder. It was then extinguished with milk and wine, and again placed %0aupon coals, and blown till ignition. %0a%0a30 As to the "nitrum" of the ancients, see B. xxxi. c. 46. %0a%0a31 « Flos'—literally the " flower." %0a%0a_ 32 " From this passage we may infer that the metal antimony was occa- %0asionally seen by the ancients, though not recognized by them as distinct %0afrom lead." — Dana's System of Mineralogy, p. 418. New York, 1850. %0a%0a33 Pliny has here mistaken the sense of the word ariap, which in the %0apassage of Dioscorides, B. v. c. 99, borrowed probably from the same %0asource, evidently means dough, and not grease. %0a%0a34 FromeAicw, "to drag"— in consequence of its viscous consistency. %0aHardoum says. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 35.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE SCORIA OF 8ILVER. %0a%0a%0a%0a117 %0a%0a%0a%0aIt has certain restringent and refrigerative effects upon bodies, %0aand, like molybdaena, of which we shall make further mention %0awhen speaking 36 of lead, is used as an ingredient in making %0aplasters, those more particularly which are to promote the %0acicatrization of wounds. It is employed also for the cure of %0atenesmus aDd dysentery, being injected in the form of a clyster %0awith myrtle-oil. It forms an ingredient, too, in the medica- %0aments known as " liparae," 36 for the removal of fleshy excres- %0acences in sores, ulcerations arising from chafing, or running %0aulcers on the head. %0a%0aThe same mines also furnish us with the preparation known %0aas " scum of silver." 37 There are three 38 varieties of it ; the %0abest, known as " chrysitis ;" the second best, the name of %0awhich is " argyritis ;" and a third kind, which is called %0a" molybditis." In most instances, too, all these tints are to %0abe found in the same cake. 39 %0a%0aThe most approved kind is that of Attica ; the next being %0athat which comes from Spain. Chrysitis is the produce of %0athe metallic vein, 40 argyritis is obtained from the silver itself, %0aand molybditis is the result of the smelting of lead, 41 a work %0athat is done at Puteoli ; to which last circumstance, in fact, mo- %0alybditis owes its name. 42 All' these substances are prepared in %0athe following manner : the metal is first melted, and then al- %0alowed to flow from a more elevated receiver into a lower. From %0athis last it is lifted by the aid of iron spits, and is then twirled %0around at the end of the spit in the midst of the flames, in %0aorder to make it all the lighter. Thus, as may be easily per- %0a%0a35 In B. xxxiv. c. 53. %0a%0a36 Cerates, adipose or oleaginous plasters. See B. xxiii. c. 81. %0a%0a37 " Spuma argenti." This he uses as a general name for fused oxide %0aof lead, the Litharge of commerce. %0a%0a38 Ajasson thinks it possible that the " chrysitis," or "golden" litharge, %0amay have been the yellow deutoxide of lead ; the argyritis, or " silver" %0alitharge, the white variety of the same deutoxide; and the "molybditis," %0aor " leaden" litharge, a general name for sulphuret of lead and silver ; of %0alead and antimony ; of lead, antimony, and bismuth ; and of lead, anti- %0amony, and copper. Or perhaps, he thinks, they may have been the respec- %0ative names of yellow or golden litharge, white or silver litharge, and terne. %0aWith the latter opinion Delafosse seems to coincide. %0a%0a39 " Tubulis." These cakes were probably made in a tubular form. %0a%0a40 "Vena ;" meaning the ore probably in its raw state, and mixed with %0aearth. All these distinctions are probably unfounded. %0a%0a11 See B. xxxiv. c. 53. « Of " Puteolana." %0a%0a%0a%0a118 %0a%0a%0a%0aplint's natural histoby. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XXXIII. %0a%0a%0a%0aceived from the name, it is in reality the scum of a substance %0ain a state of fusion — of the future metal, in fact. It differs %0afrom scoria in the same way that the scum of a liquid differs %0afrom the lees, the one 43 being an excretion thrown out by %0athe metal while purifying itself, the other* 4 an excretion of %0athe metal when purified. %0a%0aSome persons distinguish two kinds of scum of silver, and %0agive them the names of " scirerytis" and " peumene ;" 45 a third %0avariety being molybdaena, of which we shall have to make %0afurther mention when treating of lead. 46 To make this scum %0afit for use, the cakes are again broken into pieces the size %0aof a hazel-nut, and then melted, the fire being briskly blown %0awith the bellows. For the purpose of separating the charcoal %0aand ashes from it, it is then rinsed with vinegar or with wine, %0aand is so quenched. In the case of argyritis, it is recom- %0amended, in order to blanch it, to break it into pieces the size %0aof a bean, and then to boil it with water in an earthen vessel, %0afirst putting with it, wrapped in linen cloths, some new wheat %0aand barley, which are left there till they have lost the outer %0acoat. This done, they bruise the whole in mortars