rysipelas : and, %0awith myrtle and wax, it is a cure for chilblains. %0a%0aCHAP. 36. (7.) — MINIUM : FOR WHAT RELIGIOUS PURPOSES IT %0aWAS USED BY THE ANCIENTS. %0a%0aIt is also in silver-mines that minium 50 is found, a pigment %0aheld at the present day in very high estimation ; and by the %0aRomans in former times not only held in the highest estima- %0ation, but used for sacred purposes as well. Verrius enume- %0arates certain authors, upon whose testimony we find it satis- %0afactorily established that it was the custom upon festivals to %0acolour the face of the statue of Jupiter even with minium, as %0awell as the bodies 51 of triumphant generals ; and that it was %0ain this guise that Camillus celebrated his triumph. We find, %0atoo, that it is through the same religious motives that it is %0aemployed at the present day for colouring the unguents used %0aat triumphal banquets, and that it is the first duty of the %0acensors to make a contract for painting the statue of Jupiter" %0awith this colour. %0a%0aFor my own part, I am quite at a loss for the origin of this %0ausage ; but it is a well-known fact, that at the present day %0aeven, minium is in great esteem with the nations of ^Ethiopia, %0atheir nobles being in the habit of staining the body all over %0awith it, and this being the colour appropriated to the statues %0a%0a49 In this Chapter. See note 36 above. %0a%0a50 The minium spoken of in this and the following Chapter is our Cin- %0anabar, a bisulphurate of mercury. This ore is the great source of the mer- %0acury of commerce, from which it is obtained by sublimation. When pure, %0ait is the same as the manufactured vermilion of commerce. %0a%0a51 Intended, no doubt, to be typical of blood and carnage ; and indica- %0ative of a very low state of civilization. %0a%0aM See B. sxxv. c. 45. %0a%0a%0a%0a120 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLINY'S NATURAL HISTORY. [Book XXXIII. %0a%0a%0a%0aof their gods. I shall therefore use all the more diligence in %0aenquiring into all the known facts respecting it. %0a%0aCHAP. 37. — THE DISCOVERT AND ORIGIN OF MINIUM. %0a%0aTheophrastus states that, ninety years before the magis- %0atracy of Praxibulus at Athens — a date which answers to the %0ayear of our City, 439 — minium was discovered by Callias the %0aAthenian, who was in hopes to extract gold, by submitting to %0athe action of fire the red sand that was found in the silver-mines. %0aThis, he says, was the first discovery of minium. He states, %0aalso, that in his own time, it was already found in Spain, but %0aof a harsh and sandy nature ; as also in Colchis, upon a cer- %0atain inaccessible rock there, from which it was brought down %0aby the agency of darts. This, however, he says, was only an %0aadulterated kind of minium, the best of all being that pro- %0acured in the Cilbian Plains, 53 above Ephesus, the sand of which %0ahas just the colour of the kermes berry. 54 This sand, he in- %0aforms us, is first ground to powder and then washed, the %0aportion that settles at the bottom being subjected to a second %0awashing. From this circumstance, he says, arises a difference %0ain the article ; some persons being in the habit of preparing %0atheir minium with a single washing, while with others it is %0amore diluted. The best kind, however, he says, is that which %0ahas undergone a second washing. %0a%0aCHAP. 38. CINNABARIS. %0a%0aI am not surprised that this colour should have been held %0ain such high esteem ; for already, in the days of the Trojan %0a"War, rubrica 55 was highly valued, as appears from the testi- %0amony of Homer, who particularly notices the ships that were %0acoloured with it, whereas, in reference to other colours and %0apaintings, he but rarely notices them. The Greeks call this %0ared earth "miltos," and give to minium the name of "cinna- %0abaris," and hence the error 56 caused by the two meanings of %0a%0as 3 See B. v. c. 31. 54 See B. xvi. c. 12, and B. xxiv. c. 4. %0a%0a55 The same as the miltos mentioned below, " miltos" being the word %0aused by Homer, II. II. 637. This substance is totally different from the %0aminium of the preceding Chapters, and from that mentioned in c. 40. It %0ais our red ochre, peroxide of iron, mixed in a greater or less degree with %0aargillaceous earth. %0a%0as« See B. xxix. c. 8 ; where he speaks of the mistake made by the phy- %0asicians in giving mineral vermilion or minium to their patients instead of %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 40.] THE VARIOUS KINDS OF MINIUM. 121 %0a%0a%0a%0athe same word ; this being properly the name given to the %0athick matter which issues from the dragon when crushed be- %0aneath the weight of the dying elephant, mixed with the blood %0aof either animal, as already described." Indeed this last is the %0aonly colour that in painting gives a proper representation of %0ablood. This cinnabaris, too, is extremely useful as an ingre- %0adient in antidotes and various medicaments. But, by Her- %0acules ! our physicians, because minium also has the name of %0a" cinnabaris," use it as a substitute for the other, and so em- %0aploy a poison, as we shall shortly 58 show it to be. %0a%0aCnAP. 39. THE EMPLOYMENT OF CINNABARIS IN PAINTING. %0a%0aThe ancients used to paint with cinnabaris 59 those pictures %0aof one colour, which are still known among us as " monochro- %0amata." 60 They painted also with the minium of Ephesus : 61 %0abut the use of this last has been abandoned, from the vast %0atrouble which the proper keeping of the picture entailed. And %0athen besides, both these colours were thought to be too harsh ; %0athe consequence of which is, that painters have now adopted %0athe use of rubrica 62 and of sinopis, substances of which I shall %0amake further mention in the appropriate places. 63 %0a%0aCinnabaris 64 is adulterated by the agency of goats' blood, or %0aof bruised sorb-apples. The price of genuine cinnabaris is fifty %0asesterces per pound. %0a%0aCHAP. 40. THE VARIOUS KINDS OF MINIUM. THE USE MADE OF %0a%0aIT IN PAINTING. %0a%0aAccording to Juba minium is also a production of Carmania, 65 %0aand Timagenes says that it is found in ^Ethiopia. But from %0aneither of those regions is it imported to Borne, nor, indeed, %0a%0aIndian cinnabar. The latter substance is probably identical with that %0awhich is now used for varnishes, being imported from India, and still %0aknown as " dragons' blood," the resin of the Ptero-carpus draco, or Cala- %0amus palm. 57 In B. viii. c. 12. 68 In Chapter 41. %0a%0a59 The dragon's blood, mentioned in the preceding Chapter. %0a%0a60 " Single colour paintings." See B. xxxv. cc. 5, 11, 34, 36. %0a%0a61 Mentioned in Chapter 37. %0a%0aM The " miltos" of the preceding Chapter. See Note 55 above. %0a63 In B. xxxv. c. 13, et seq. %0a%0a61 He is here speaking of our cinnabar, or vermilion, mentioned in %0aChapter 36. 65 See B. vi. cc 27, 28. 32. %0a%0a%0a%0a122 %0a%0a%0a%0apunt's NATURAL HISTORY. [Book XXXIII. %0a%0a%0a%0afrom hardly any other quarter but Spain ; that of most note %0acoming from Sisapo, 66 a territory of .Baetica, the mine of mi- %0anium there forming a part of the revenues of the Roman %0apeople. Indeed there is nothing guarded with a more constant %0acircumspection ; for it is not allowable to reduce and refine %0athe ore upon the spot, it being brought to Rome in a crude %0astate and under seal, to the amount of about two thousand %0apounds per annum. At Eome, the process of washing is per- %0aformed, and, in the sale of it, the price is regulated by statute ; %0ait not being allowed to exceed 67 seventy sesterces per pound. %0aThere are numerous ways, however, of adulterating it, a source %0aof considerable plunder to the company. 68 %0a%0aFor there is, in fact, another kind 69 of minium, found in most %0asilver-mines as well as lead-mines, and prepared by the calcina- %0ation of certain stones that are found mixed with the metallic %0avein — not the minerals, however, to the fluid humours of %0awhich we have given 10 the name of quicksilver ; for if those are %0asubjected to the action of fire they will yield silver — but another %0akind of stone 7 ' that is found with them. These barren 72 stones, %0atoo, may be recognized by their uniform leaden colour, and it %0ais only when in the furnace that they turn red. After being %0aduly calcined they are pulverized, and thus form a minium of %0asecond-rate quality, known to but very few, and far inferior %0ato the produce of the native sand that we have mentioned." %0aIt is with this substance, then, as also with syricum, that %0athe genuine minium is adulterated in the manufactories of the %0acompany. How syricum is prepared we shall describe in the %0aappropriate place. 74 One motive, however, for giving an under- %0acoat of 6yricum to minium, is the evident saving of expense %0athat results therefrom. Minium, too, in another way affords a %0avery convenient opportunity to painters for pilfering, by wash- %0a%0a66 See B. iii. c. 3, Vol. I. p. 163. He alludes to the district of Almaden, %0ain Andalusia, still famous for its quicksilver mines. %0a%0a67 "When sold by the "publicani," or farmers of the revenue. %0a%0a68 Of the publicani. %0a%0a69 Red oxide of lead, a much inferior pigment to cinnabar, or the minium %0aof Chapter 36. ™ In Chapter 32 of this Book. %0a%0a71 Dana informs us that minium is usually associated with galena and %0awith calamine. Syst. Mineral, p. 495. %0a%0a72 "Steriles." Barren of silver, probably; though Hardouin thinks %0athat it means " barren of lead." Holland renders it " barraine and void %0aof the right vermilion." ™ In Chapter 37 . 74 B. xxxv. c. 24. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 40.] THE VARIOUS KINDS OF JILNITJM. %0a%0a%0a%0a123 %0a%0a%0a%0aing their brushes, 15 filled with the colouring matter, every now %0aand then. The minium of course falls to the bottom, and is %0athus so much gained by the thief. %0a%0aGenuine minium ought to have the brilliant colour of the %0akermes berry ; 76 but when that of inferior quality is used for %0awalls, the brightness of it is sure to be tarnished by the %0amoisture, and this too, although the substance itself is a sort %0aof metallic mildew. In the mines of Sisapo, the veins are %0acomposed exclusively of the sandy particles of minium, with- %0aout the intermixture of any silver whatever ; the practice being %0ato melt it like gold. Minium is assayed by the agency of gold %0ain a state of incandescence : if it has been adulterated, it will %0aturn black, but if genuine, it retains its colour. I find it %0astated also that minium is adulterated with lime ; the proper %0amode of detecting which, is similarly to employ a sheet of red %0ahot iron, if there should happen to be no gold at hand. %0a%0aTo objects painted with minium the action of the sun and %0amoon is highly injurious. The proper method of avoiding %0athis inconvenience, is to dry the wall, and then to apply, with %0aa hair brush, hot Punic wax, melted with oil ; after which, %0athe varnish must be heated, with an application of gall-nuts, %0aburnt to a red heat, till it quite perspires. This done, it must %0abe smoothed down with rollers 77 made of wax, and then polish- %0aed with clean linen cloths, like marble, when made to shine. %0aPersons employed in the manufactories in preparing minium %0aprotect the face with masks of loose bladder-skin, in order to %0aavoid inhaling the dust, which is highly pernicious ; the cover- %0aing being at the same time sufficiently transparent to admit of %0abeing seen through. %0a%0aMinium is employed also for writing 78 in books ; and the %0aletters made with it being more distinct, even on gold or mar- %0able, it is used for the inscriptions upon tombs. %0a%0a75 When hired by the job for colouring walls or objects of art. See %0aB. xxxv. c. 12. %0a16 See B. xvi. c. 12, and B. xxiv. c. 4. %0a%0a77 " Candelis." The Abate Requeno thinks that these "candelse" were %0aused as a delicate cauteriuro, simply to keep the wax soft, that it might %0areceive a polish from the friction of the linen. %0a%0a78 Hence the use of it in the middle ages ; a reminiscence of which still %0aexists in our word "rubric." %0a%0a%0a%0a124 %0a%0a%0a%0apliny's natural iiistory. [Rook XXXIII. %0a%0a%0a%0aCHAP. 41. (8.) — HYDRARGYKOS. REMEDIES DERIVED FROM %0aMINIUM. %0a%0aHuman industry has also discovered a method of extracting %0ahydrargyros 79 from the inferior minium, a substitute for quick- %0asilver, the further mention of which was deferred, a few pages %0abefore, 80 to the present occasion. There are two methods of %0apreparing this substance ; either by pounding minium and %0avinegar with a brazen pestle and mortar, or else by putting %0aminium into flat earthen pans, covered with a lid, and then %0aenclosed in an iron seething-pot well luted with potter's clay. %0aA fire is then lighted under the pans, and the flame kept con- %0atinually burning by the aid of the bellows ; which done, the %0aSteam is carefully removed, that is found adhering to the lid, %0abeing like silver in colour, and similar to water in its fluidity. %0aThis liquid, too, is easily made to separate in globules, which, %0afrom their fluid nature, readily unite. 81 %0a%0aAs it is a fact generally admitted, that minium is a poison, 82 %0aI look upon all the recipes given as highly dangerous which %0arecommend its employment for medicinal purposes ; with the %0aexception, perhaps, of those cases in which it is applied to the %0ahead or abdomen, for the purpose of arresting haemorrhage, %0adue care being taken that it is not allowed to penetrate to the %0aviscera, or to touch any sore. Beyond such cases as these, for %0amy own part, I should never recommend it to be used in %0amedicine. %0a%0aCHAP. 42. THE METHOD OF GILDING SILVER. %0a%0aAt the present day silver is gilded almost exclusively by %0athe agency of hydrargyros j 83 and a similar method should %0aalways be employed in laying gold leaf upon copper. But %0athe same fraud which ever shows itself so extremely inge-