 this precious commodity. %0a%3c %0a%3c The gold that is extracted from shafts is known by some %0a%3c persons as " canalicium," and by others as " canaliense ;" 30 it %0a%3c is found adhering to the gritty crust of marble, 31 and, altogether %0a%3c different from the form in which it sparkles in the sapphirus 32 %0a%3c of the East, and in the stone of Thebais 33 and other gems, it %0a%3c is seen interlaced with the molecules of the marble. The %0a%3c channels of these veins are found running in various directions %0a%3c along the sides of the shafts, and hence the name of the gold %0a%3c they yield — "canalicium." 34 In these shafts, too, the su- %0a%3c perincumbent earth is kept from falling in by means of wooden %0a%3c pillars. The substance that is extracted is first broken up, %0a%3c and then washed ; after which it is subjected to the action of %0a%3c fire, and ground to a fine powder. This powder is known as %0a%3c " apitascudes," while the silver which becomes disengaged in %0a%3c the 35 furnace has the name of " sudor" 36 given to it. The im- %0a%3c %0a%3c riferous deposits by the name of segullo. He also doubts the correctness of %0a%3c Pliny's assertion as to the produce of the mines of Dalmatia. %0a%3c %0a%3c 28 See B. xxxiv. c. 47. %0a%3c %0a%3c 29 We learfl from Ajasson that numerous pits or shafts are still to be %0a%3c seen in Spain, from which the Bomans extracted gold. At Biotento, he %0a%3c says, there are several of them. so Both meaning " channel gold." %0a%3c %0a%3c si "Marnioris glares." Under this name, he no doubt means quartz and %0a%3c schist 32 See B xxxvii. c. 39. ^ g ee g xxxv i. c . 13. %0a%3c %0a%3c 34 "Channel-gold" or " trench- gold." %0a%3c %0a%3c 35 Becoming volatilized, and attaching itself in crystals to the side of %0a%3c the chimney. %0a%3c %0a%3c 36 Or "sweat." This ''sweat" or ''silver" would in reality be a %0a%3c general name for all the minerals that were volatilized by the heat of the %0a%3c furnace ; while under the name of "scoria" would be comprised pyrites, %0a%3c quartz, petrosilex, and other similar substances. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 21.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c HOW GOLD IS FOUND. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 101 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c purities that escape by the chimney, as in the case of all %0a%3c other metals, are known by the name of " scoria." In the %0a%3c case of gold, this scoria is broken up a second time, and melted %0a%3c over again. The crucibles used for this purpose are made of %0a%3c " tasconium," 37 a white earth similar to potter's clay in ap- %0a%3c pearance ; there being no other substance capable of with- %0a%3c standing the strong current of air, the action of the fixe, and %0a%3c the intense heat of the melted metal. %0a%3c %0a%3c The third method of obtaining gold surpasses the labours %0a%3c of the Giants 38 even : by the aid of galleries driven to a long %0a%3c distance, mountains are excavated by the light of torches, the %0a%3c duration of which forms the set times for work, the workmen %0a%3c never seeing the light of day for many months together. %0a%3c These mines are known as " arrugiae ;" 89 and not unfrequently %0a%3c clefts are formed on a sudden, the earth sinks in, and the work- %0a%3c men are crushed beneath ; so that it would really appear less rash %0a%3c to go in search of pearls and purples at the bottom of the sea, %0a%3c so much more dangerous to ourselves have we made the earth %0a%3c than the water ! Hence it is, that in this kind of mining, %0a%3c arches are left at frequent intervals for the purpose of sup- %0a%3c porting the weight of the mountain above. In mining either %0a%3c by shaft or by gallery, barriers of silex are met with, which %0a%3c have to be driven asunder by the aid of fire and vinegar ; 40 or %0a%3c more frequently, as this method fills the gallerieswith suffocating %0a%3c vapours and smoke, to be broken to pieces with bruising- %0a%3c machines shod with pieces of iron weighing one hundred and %0a%3c fifty pounds : which done, the fragments are carried out on the %0a%3c workmen's shoulders, night and day, each man passing them %0a%3c on to his neighbour in the dark, it being only those at the pit's %0a%3c mouth that ever see the light. In cases where the bed of silex %0a%3c appears too thick to admit of being penetrated, the miner traces %0a%3c alongthe sides of it, and so turns it. Andyet, after all, the labour %0a%3c entailed by this silex is looked upon as comparatively easy, there %0a%3c being an earth — a kind of potter's clay mixed with gravel, %0a%3c " gangadia" by name, which it is almost impossible to overcome. %0a%3c This earth has to be attacked with iron wedges and hammers %0a%3c %0a%3c 87 The cupel or crucible is still known in Spain by the name of tasco. %0a%3c %0a%3c 38 Who were said to have heaped one mountain on another in their war %0a%3c with the gods. %0a%3c %0a%3c 39 Deep mines in Spain are still called arrugia, a term also used to %0a%3c signify gold beneath the surface. According to Grimm, arrnzi was the %0a%3c ancient High German name lor iron. 40 See E. xxiii. c. 27. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 102 pliny's natural histokt. [Book XXXIII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c like those previously mentioned, 41 and it is generally considered %0a%3c that there is nothing more stubborn in existence — except in- %0a%3c deed the greed for gold, which is the most stubborn of all things?. %0a%3c %0a%3c When these operations are all completed, beginning at the %0a%3c last, they cut away 42 the wooden pillars at the point where %0a%3c they support the roof: the coming downfall gives warning, %0a%3c which is instantly perceived by the sentinel, and by him only, %0a%3c who is set to watch upon a peak of the same mountain. By %0a%3c voice as well as by signals, he orders the workmen to be im- %0a%3c mediately summoned from their labours, and at the same %0a%3c moment takes to flight himself. The mountain, rent to pieces, %0a%3c is cleft asunder, hurling its debris to a distance with a crash %0a%3c which it is impossible for the human imagination to conceive ; %0a%3c and from the midst of a cloud of dust, of a density quite in- %0a%3c credible, the victorious miners gaze upon this downfall of %0a%3c Nature. Nor yet even then are they sure of gold, nor indeed %0a%3c were they by any means certain that there was any to he %0a%3c found when they first began to excavate, it being quite suf- %0a%3c ficient, as an inducement to undergo such perils and to incur %0a%3c such vast expense, to entertain the hope that they shall obtain %0a%3c what they so eagerly desire. %0a%3c %0a%3c Another labour, too, quite equal to this, and one which en- %0a%3c tails even greater expense, is that of bringing rivers 43 from %0a%3c the more elevated mountain heights, a distance in many in- %0a%3c stances of one hundred miles perhaps, for the purpose of %0a%3c washing these debris. The channels thus formed are called %0a%3c "corrugi," from our word " corrivatio," 44 1 suppose ; and even %0a%3c when these are once made, they entail a thousand fresh labours. %0a%3c The fall, for instance, must be steep, that the water may he %0a%3c precipitated, so to say, rather than flow ; and it is in this %0a%3c manner that it is brought from the most elevated points. %0a%3c Then, too, vallies and crevasses have to be united by the aid of %0a%3c aqueducts, and in another place impassable rocks have to be %0a%3c hewn away, and forced to make room for hollowed troughs of %0a%3c wood ; the person hewing them hanging suspended all the %0a%3c time with ropes, so that to a spectator who views the operations %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 The breaking-machines, used for crushing the silex. %0a%3c %0a%3c 42 " Csedunt" is certainly a preferable reading to " cadunt," though the %0a%3c latter is given by the Bamberg MS. %0a%3c %0a%3c 43 A similar method of washing auriferous earth or sand in the mines, %0a%3c is still employed in some cases. %0a%3c %0a%3c 44 "The bringing of water into one channel," %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 21.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c HOW GOLD IS FOUNT). %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 103 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c from a distance, the workmen have all the appearance, not so %0a%3c much of wild beasts, as of birds upon the wing. 45 Hanging %0a%3c thus suspended in most instances, they take the levels, and %0a%3c trace with lines the course the water is to take ; and thus, %0a%3c where there is no room even for man to plant a footstep, are %0a%3c rivers traced out by the hand of man. The water, too, is con- %0a%3c sidered in an unfit state for washing, if the current of the %0a%3c river carries any mud along with it. The kind of earth tbat %0a%3c yields this mud is known as " urium;" 46 and hence it is that %0a%3c in tracing out these channels, they carry the water over beds %0a%3c of silex or pebbles, and carefully avoid this urium. When %0a%3c they have reached the head of the fall, at the very brow of the %0a%3c mountain, reservoirs are hollowed out, a couple of hundred %0a%3c feet in length and breadth, and some ten feet in depth. In %0a%3c these reservoirs there are generally five sluices left, about %0a%3c three feet square ; so that, the moment the reservoir is filled, the %0a%3c floodgates are struck away, and the torrent bursts forth with %0a%3c such a degree of violence as to roll onwards any fragments of %0a%3c rock which may obstruct its passage. %0a%3c %0a%3c "When they have reached the level ground, too, there is %0a%3c still another labour that awaits them. Trenches — known as %0a%3c " agogae" 47 — have to be dug for the passage of the water; and %0a%3c these, at regular intervals, have a layer of ulex placed at the %0a%3c bottom. This ulex 48 is a plant like rosemary in appearance, %0a%3c rough and prickly, and well-adapted for arresting any pieces %0a%3c of gold that may be carried along. The sides, too, are closed %0a%3c in with planks, and are supported by arches when carried over %0a%3c steep and precipitous spots. The earth, carried onwards in %0a%3c the stream, arrives at the sea at last, and thus is the shattered %0a%3c mountain washed away ; causes which have greatly tended to %0a%3c extend the shores of Spain by these encroachments upon the %0a%3c deep. It is also by the agency of canals of this description %0a%3c that the material, excavated at the cost of such immense la- %0a%3c bour by the process previously described, 49 is washed and car- %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 Or as Holland quaintly renders it, " Some flying spirit or winged %0a%3c devill of the air." %0a%3c 44 Magnesian carbonate of lime, or dolomite, Ajasson thinks.- %0a%3c 47 From the Greek, aywy?}. %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 It does not appear to have been identified ; and it can hardly be %0a%3c the same as the Ulex Europseus of modern Natural History, our Furze %0a%3c cr Gorse. %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 That of sinking shafts, described already in this Chapter. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 104 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint's natuuax uistobt. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXXIII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ricd away ; for otherwise the shafts would soon be choked up %0a%3c by it. %0a%3c %0a%3c The gold found by excavating with galleries does not require %0a%3c to be melted, but is pure gold at once. In these excavations, %0a%3c too, it is found in lumps, as also in the shafts which are sunk, %0a%3c sometimes exceeding ten pounds even. The names given to %0a%3c these lumps are " palagse," and " palacurnse," 60 while the gold %0a%3c found in small grains is known as " baluce." The ulex that %0a%3c is used for the above purpose is dried and burnt, after which %0a%3c the ashes of it are washed upon a bed of grassy turf, in order %0a%3c that the gold may be deposited thereupon. %0a%3c %0a%3c Asturia, Gallaocia, and Lusitania furnish in this manner, %0a%3c yearly, according to some authorities, twenty thousand pounds' %0a%3c weight of gold, the produce of Asturia forming the major part. %0a%3c Indeed, there is no part of the world that for centuries has %0a%3c maintained such a continuous fertility in gold. I have already' 1 %0a%3c mentioned that by an ancient decree of the senate, the soil of %0a%3c Italy has been protected from these researches ; otherwise, %0a%3c there would be no land more fertile in metals. There is ex- > %0a%3c tant also a censorial law relative to the gold mines of Victumulae, %0a%3c in the territory of Vercellse, 52 by which the farmers of the %0a%3c revenue were forbidden to employ more than five thousand %0a%3c men at the works. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 22. OEPIMENT. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is also one other method of procuring gold ; by making %0a%3c it from orpiment, 53 a mineral dug from the surface of the earth %0a%3c in Syria, and much used by painters. It is just the colour of %0a%3c gold, but brittle, like mirror-stone, 54 in fact. This substance %0a%3c greatly excited the hopes of the Emperor Caius, 56 a prince who %0a%3c was most greedy for gold. He accordingly had a large quantity %0a%3c of it melted, and really did obtain some excellent gold ; i6 but %0a%3c then the proportion was so extremely small, that he found him- %0a%3c self a loser thereby. Such was the result of an experiment %0a%3c prompted solely by avarice : and this too, although the price %0a%3c %0a%3c 50 All these names, no doubt, are of Spanish origin, although Salmasius %0a%3c would assign them a Greek one. %0a%3c %0a%3c 5! In B. iii. c. 24. 52 g ee g iii. c . 21. %0a%3c %0a%3c 53 " Auripigmentum." Yellow sulphuret of arsenic. See B. xxxiv. c. 5G. %0a%3c %0a%3c 54 "Lapis specularis." See B. xxxvi. c. 45 . 55 Caligula. %0a%3c %0a%3c 66 It was accidently mixed with the ore of arsenic, no doubt" unless in- %0a%3c deed, the emperor was imposed upon. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 24.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE FIRST STATUES OF GOLD. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 105 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c of the orpiment itself was no more than four denarii per pound. %0a%3c Since his