ioned ; and thus is it painted itself before it serves %0a%3c to paint. It is of considerable importance, too, that it should %0a%3c be absorbent and readily take the dye : indeed, if it does not %0a%3c speedily take the colour, scytanum and turbistum' 8 are added to %0a%3c the dye ; such being the name of two drugs which compel it to %0a%3c absorb the colouring matter. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 27. THE USE MADE OF CHRYSOCOLLA IN PAINTING. %0a%3c %0a%3c _ When chrysocolla has been thus dyed, painters call it " oro- %0a%3c bitis," and distinguish two kinds of it, the cleansed 79 orobitis, 60 %0a%3c which is kept for making lomentum, 81 and the liquid, the balls %0a%3c %0a%3c 76 The " Keseda luteola," Dyer's weed, or "Wild woad. See Beckmann's %0a%3c Hist. Inv. Vol. I. p. 478—481, where the identity of the Chrysocolla of %0a%3c the ancients is discussed at considerable length. %0a%3c %0a%3c 77 As to the identity of this substance, see B. xxxv. c. 52. %0a%3c 73 These drugs have not been identified. %0a%3c %0a%3c ™ " Elutam." Though this is the reading given by the Bamberg MS., %0a%3c "luteam" seems preferable; a name owing, probably, to its beino- coloured %0a%3c with the plant " lutum," as mentioned at the end of this Chapter? %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 So called, probably, from being made up into little balls resembling %0a%3c the "orobus" or vetch. %0a%3c %0a%3c « A powder, probably, prepared from « caeruleum." See the end of the %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 27.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE USE MADE OP CHETSOCOLLA. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 109 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c being dissolved for use by evaporation. 82 Both these kinds %0a%3c are prepared in Cyprus, 83 but the most esteemed is that made %0a%3c in Armenia, the next best being that of Macedonia : it is Spain, %0a%3c however, that produces the most. The great point of its ex- %0a%3c cellence consists in its producing exactly the tint of corn when %0a%3c in a state of the freshest verdure. 84 Before now, we have 