f white lead ; K white lead with white lead, %0a%3c by the agency of oil ; stannum, with copper file-dust ; and %0a%3c silver, with stannum. 97 %0a%3c %0a%3c For smelting copper and iron, pine-wood is the best, Egypt- %0a%3c ian papyrus being also very good for the purpose. Gold is %0a%3c melted most easily with a fire made of chaff'. 98 Limestone %0a%3c and Thracian stone" are ignited by the agency of water, this %0a%3c last being extinguished by the application of oil. Fire, how- %0a%3c ever, is extinguished most readily by the application of vinegar, %0a%3c viscus, 1 and unboiled eggs. Earth will under no circumstance %0a%3c ignite. When charcoal has been once quenched, and then again %0a%3c ignited, it gives out a greater heat than before. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 31. (6.) SILVER. %0a%3c %0a%3c After stating these facts, we come to speak of silver ore, %0a%3c the next 2 folly of mankind. Silver is never found but in %0a%3c shafts sunk deep in the ground, there being no indications to %0a%3c raise hopes of its existence, no shining sparkles, as in the case %0a%3c of gold. The earth in which it is found is sometimes red, some- %0a%3c times of an ashy hue. It is impossible, too, to melt 3 it, except %0a%3c %0a%3c 95 As to the " cadmia " of Pliny, see B. xxxiv. c. 22. %0a%3c %0a%3c 96 " Plumbum album." Tin, most probably. See B. xxxiv. cc. 47, 48, %0a%3c 49. Also Beckmanu's Hist. Inv., Vol. II. p. 219. Bohn's Edition. %0a%3c %0a%3c 97 Of doubtful identity. See B. xxxiv. c. 48. %0a%3c %0a%3c 98 See Chapter 19 of this Look. %0a%3c %0a%3c 99 "Thracius lapis." This stone, which is mentioned also by Nicander, %0a%3c Galen, Simplicius, and Dioscorides, bas not been identified. Holland bas %0a%3c the following Note on this passage: " Which some take for pit-cole, or sea- %0a%3c cole rather, such as commeth from Newcastle by sea ; or rather, a kind of %0a%3c jeat (jet)." In either case, be is probably wide of the mark, neither coal %0a%3c nor jet igniting on the application of w