 the best of all being that pro- %0a%3c cured in the Cilbian Plains, 53 above Ephesus, the sand of which %0a%3c has just the colour of the kermes berry. 54 This sand, he in- %0a%3c forms us, is first ground to powder and then washed, the %0a%3c portion that settles at the bottom being subjected to a second %0a%3c washing. From this circumstance, he says, arises a difference %0a%3c in the article ; some persons being in the habit of preparing %0a%3c their minium with a single washing, while with others it is %0a%3c more diluted. The best kind, however, he says, is that which %0a%3c has undergone a second washing. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 38. CINNABARIS. %0a%3c %0a%3c I am not surprised that this colour should have been held %0a%3c in such high esteem ; for already, in the days of the Trojan %0a%3c "War, rubrica 55 was highly valued, as appears from the testi- %0a%3c mony of Homer, who particularly notices the ships that were %0a%3c coloured with it, whereas, in reference to other colours and %0a%3c paintings, he but rarely notices them. The Greeks call this %0a%3c red earth "miltos," and give to minium the name of "cinna- %0a%3c baris," and hence the error 56 caused by the two meanings of %0a%3c %0a%3c s 3 See B. v. c. 31. 54 See B. xvi. c. 12, and B. xxiv. c. 4. %0a%3c %0a%3c 55 The same as the miltos mentioned below, " miltos" being the word %0a%3c used by Homer, II. II. 637. This substance is totally different from the %0a%3c minium of the preceding Chapters, and from that mentioned in c. 40. It %0a%3c is our red ochre, peroxide of iron, mixed in a greater or less degree with %0a%3c argillaceous earth. %0a%3c %0a%3c s« See B. xxix. c. 8 ; where he speaks of the mistake made by the phy- %0a%3c sicians in giving mineral vermilion or minium to their patients instead of %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 40.] THE VARIOUS KINDS OF MINIUM. 121 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c the same word ; this being properly the name given to the %0a%3c thick matter which issues from the dragon