hough the substance itself is a sort %0a%3c of metallic mildew. In the mines of Sisapo, the veins are %0a%3c composed exclusively of the sandy particles of minium, with- %0a%3c out the intermixture of any silver whatever ; the practice being %0a%3c to melt it like gold. Minium is assayed by the agency of gold %0a%3c in a state of incandescence : if it has been adulterated, it will %0a%3c turn black, but if genuine, it retains its colour. I find it %0a%3c stated also that minium is adulterated with lime ; the proper %0a%3c mode of detecting which, is similarly to employ a sheet of red %0a%3c hot iron, if there should happen to be no gold at hand. %0a%3c %0a%3c To objects painted with minium the action of the sun and %0a%3c moon is highly injurious. The proper method of avoiding %0a%3c this inconvenience, is to dry the wall, and then to apply, with %0a%3c a hair brush, hot Punic wax, melted with oil ; after which, %0a%3c the varnish must be heated, with an application of gall-nuts, %0a%3c burnt to a red heat, till it quite perspires. This done, it must %0a%3c be smoothed down with rollers 77 made of wax, and then polish- %0a%3c ed with clean linen cloths, like marble, when made to shine. %0a%3c Persons employed in the manufactories in preparing minium %0a%3c protect the face with masks of loose bladder-skin, in order to %0a%3c avoid inhaling the dust, which is highly pernicious ; the cover- %0a%3c ing being at the same time sufficiently transparent to admit of %0a%3c being seen through. %0a%3c %0a%3c Minium is employed also for writing 78 in books ; and the %0a%3c letters made with it being more distinct, even on gold or mar- %0a%3c ble, it is used for the inscriptions upon tombs. %0a%3c %0a%3c 75 When hired by the job for colouring walls or objects of art. See %0a%3c B. xxxv. c. 12. %0a%3c 16 See B. xvi. c. 12, and B. xxiv. c. 4. %0a%3c %0a%3c 77 " Candelis." The Abate Requeno thinks that these "candelse" were %0a%3c used as a delicate cauteriuro, simply to keep the 