esent day silver is gilded almost exclusively by %0a%3c the agency of hydrargyros j 83 and a similar method should %0a%3c always be employed in laying gold leaf upon copper. But %0a%3c the same fraud which ever shows itself so extremely inge- %0a%3c nious in all departments of human industry, has devised a %0a%3c %0a%3c 79 Or artificial quicksilver. In reality, hydrargyrus is prepared from the %0a%3c genuine minium of Pliny, the cinnabar mentioned in Chapter 36 : it being %0a%3c obtained by the sublimation of 6ulphuret of mercury %0a%3c %0a%3c 80 In Chapters 20 and 32. %0a%3c %0a%3c 81 This, probably, is the meaning of " lubrico humore comnluere " %0a%3c 83 See the end of Chapter 38. r %0a%3c %0a%3c 83 Artificial quicksilver is still used for this purpose. See Note 24 to %0a%3c Chapter 32 of this Book ; also Beckmann's Hist. Inv. Vol. II. p. 295. %0a%3c Bohris Edition. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 44.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE DIFFERENT KINDS OF SILTER. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 125 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c plan of substituting an inferior material, as already men- %0a%3c tioned. 84 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 43. — TOUCHSTONES FOR TESTING GOLD. %0a%3c %0a%3c A description of gold and silver is necessarily accompanied %0a%3c by that of the stone known as " coticula." 85 In former times, %0a%3c according to Theophrastus, this stone was nowhere to be %0a%3c found, except in the river Tmolus, 86 but at the present day it is %0a%3c found in numerous places. By some persons it is known as %0a%3c the " Heraclian," and by others as the "Lydian" stone. It %0a%3c is found in pieces of moderate size, and never exceeding four %0a%3c inches in length by two in breadth. The side that has lain %0a%3c facing the sun is superior 87 to that which has lain next to the %0a%3c ground. Persons of experience in these matters, when they %0a%3c have scraped a particle off the ore with this stone, as -with a %0a%3c file, can tell in a moment the proportion of gold there is in it, %